width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">penalties for early withdrawal</a>. It=E2=80=99s an inc=
entive to keep your money in lira, in the bank, instead of either exchangin=
g it for dollars (bad for the exchange rate) or spending it (bad for inflat=
ion).</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What is this? One way to think of it =
is that it is a selective currency peg: Turkey will defend the value of the=
 lira against the dollar, but only for certain retail accounts. The general=
 way that a currency peg works is that you commit to doing whatever it take=
s to defend the peg, and therefore everyone assumes that the peg is solid, =
and therefore nobody sells your currency and you don=E2=80=99t have to do a=
nything to defend the peg.=C2=A0If depositors=C2=A0are guaranteed not to lo=
se value by keeping their money in lira, then there is no reason for them t=
o sell lira to buy dollars, so no one will sell, so the lira won=E2=80=99t =
go down, so Turkey won=E2=80=99t have to pay anything out on this guarantee=
.[1]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another way to think of it is that it =
is a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26137490.2866=
58/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMTcv=
dGl0YW5pdW0tZ290LWNydXNoZWQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTIyMjIxX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl=
1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjExMjIyJnV0bV9jYW1wYW=
